Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your view model:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
            .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                          "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/swipe back with `OnNavigating`

The custom button handles taps, but you also need to catch system back (Android back gesture, swipe). In `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so the guard only fires on back navigation, not forward pushes.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the toolbar button; `OnNavigating` catches system back gestures.
